Edition:
Quote: <i>Pimelea prostrata</i> Pinatoro; Strathmore weed... Part eaten : The berries. No other part of the plants should be eaten as Strathmore weed has been known to poison livestock.
Notes:

Date: 0/0/1970
Source: Grasslands of NZ
Author: LEVY
Vol / Page: 305
Edition:
Quote: Strathmore weed, a low-growing shrubby plant found on poor, friable soils, if eaten when stock are forced on it in a holding paddock, may cause staggers and death, particularly if the stock are afterwards driven.
